---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Cinderella Uncovered — The Disney Deception — Nazaryah"
  description="The solar myth behind the glass slipper — three thousand years of sun-goddess worship in a ballgown."
>
  <div class="sw-wrap">

    <!-- ── HERO ── -->
    <section class="sw-hero">
      <a href="/disney" class="sw-back">&#8592; The Disney Deception</a>
      <p class="sw-label">&#8213; The Disney Deception &#8213;</p>
      <h1 class="sw-title">Cinderella Uncovered</h1>
      <p class="sw-sub">
        A solar myth in a ballgown — the sun-maiden's descent and return
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- ── MODE BAR ── -->
    <div class="sw-mode-bar">
      <button id="btn-quick" class="sw-mode-btn sw-mode-active" data-tip="Fits between bath time and bedtime.">&#9654; Quick Read</button>
      <span class="sw-mode-divider">&#8213;</span>
      <button id="btn-full" class="sw-mode-btn" data-tip="This is why they invented coffee.">Full Study</button>
    </div>

    <!-- ── QUICK READ PANEL ── -->
    <div id="panel-quick">

      <section class="sw-section">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-kicker">You grew up on this story. So did your mom. So did your daughters. Have you ever stopped to ask where it actually came from?</p>
          <p>Not from Disney. Not from the Brothers Grimm. The Cinderella story is over three thousand years old. The oldest version was written down in Egypt — and it wasn't a fairy tale. It was a sun story. A story about the daughter of the sun who rises from the ashes and marries the king.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="sw-section sw-section-alt">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-section-heading">Look at the Pieces</p>
          <p>Every single element of Cinderella has a pagan fingerprint on it. Once you see them, you can't unsee them:</p>
          <ul class="sw-list">
            <li><strong>The cinders.</strong> Her name means "ash girl" in every language. The hearth was sacred to Vesta — her priestesses kept a fire burning in her honor. Cinderella sleeps in the ashes and rises from them, just like the sun rises from the dark each morning.</li>
            <li><strong>Midnight.</strong> Everything turns back at twelve — the deepest moment of darkness. That's the solar cycle. The sun dies at midnight and is reborn at dawn.</li>
            <li><strong>The pumpkin.</strong> A harvest symbol — the same symbol at the center of Halloween. Cinderella's carriage and the jack-o'-lantern come from the same pagan harvest tradition.</li>
            <li><strong>The glass slipper.</strong> Glass catches light. In ancient symbolism, it was a sun-token — the thing only the true sun-maiden could wear.</li>
            <li><strong>The twelve strokes.</strong> Twelve signs of the zodiac. Twelve hours of night. Not a random number.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="sw-section">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-section-heading">And Then There's the Fairy Godmother</p>
          <p>Be honest — if a stranger showed up in your living room tonight, waved a stick, and turned your minivan into a carriage, you'd call 911 and then your pastor. But in the movie? She's the sweetest part. Children love her. Adults buy the costume.</p>
          <p>The fairy godmother is a witch. Not a metaphorical witch. She casts spells, transforms living creatures, and grants wishes you send up into the stars. Scripture calls every one of those things an abomination (Deuteronomy 18:10–12). The word "fairy" itself comes from the pagan fates — spirits of destiny worshipped across Europe for centuries.</p>
          <div class="sw-scripture-block">
            <p class="sw-scripture-label">&#9656; Jeremiah 17:9</p>
            <p>"The heart is deceitful above all things, and desperately wicked." — the opening song "A Dream Is a Wish Your Heart Makes" teaches the exact opposite.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="sw-section sw-section-alt">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-section-heading">What Is Your Daughter Actually Learning?</p>
          <p>Strip the music and the colors away and the story teaches six things:</p>
          <ul class="sw-list">
            <li>Your heart's wish is a prayer, and the stars will answer it.</li>
            <li>A magical stranger will show up to rescue you.</li>
            <li>Spells will change your life.</li>
            <li>Your worth is revealed when the prince sees you at the ball.</li>
            <li>The right man will find you through a magical token.</li>
            <li>The goal is the wedding. That's where the story ends.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>None of these are what Scripture teaches. Not one. And your daughter is watching this movie on repeat.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="sw-section">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-section-heading">So Now What?</p>
          <p>You don't have to throw the DVD in the fire tonight. But maybe the next time she puts it on, you sit down with her. Ask her what she thinks about the fairy godmother. Ask her where she thinks wishes actually go. Ask her what she thinks Yahuah would say about a kingdom where the prince finds his bride by a magic slipper instead of by meeting her parents.</p>
          <p>Proverbs 31 is the real version. A woman praised not because she's beautiful at the ball, but because she fears Yahuah, works with her hands, loves her family, and speaks wisdom. That's the story you want your daughters in.</p>
          <div class="sw-scripture-block">
            <p class="sw-scripture-label">&#9656; Proverbs 31:30</p>
            <p>"Favour is deceitful, and beauty is vain: but a woman that feareth Yahuah, she shall be praised."</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="sw-footer-quote">
        <div class="sw-summary-block">
          <p class="sw-summary-label">&#9656; The Short Version</p>
          <p class="sw-summary-text">Cinderella is the sun-maiden of ancient paganism — the ash-girl who rises from the hearth, marries the sun-king at the stroke of the solar hour, and teaches little girls to wish upon stars, trust in sorceresses, and measure their worth by the moment they are seen.</p>
        </div>
        <p class="sw-cta-link" style="text-align:center; margin-top:1.5rem;">
          <button id="btn-full-cta" class="sw-mode-btn" style="font-size:0.75rem; letter-spacing:2px;">&#8594; Read the Full Study</button>
        </p>
      </section>

    </div><!-- /panel-quick -->

    <!-- ── FULL STUDY PANEL ── -->
    <div id="panel-full" style="display:none">

      <section class="sw-section">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-section-heading">The Story Is Much Older Than Disney</p>
          <p>The Cinderella tale-type has a special folklore catalog number — Aarne-Thompson Type 510A. Over 500 distinct versions have been collected across cultures, reaching back to the ninth century in China (Ye Xian, around AD 860) and possibly the Greek historian Strabo's Rhodopis in the first century BC.</p>
          <p>Rhodopis is the critical early version. A Greek slave girl in Egypt has her sandal carried off by an eagle, which drops it in the lap of the Pharaoh. The Pharaoh searches the kingdom for the owner of the sandal and makes her his queen. The eagle is the bird of the sun god. The sandal is the sun-symbol of the maiden. The entire story is a solar marriage myth.</p>
          <div class="sw-scripture-block">
            <p class="sw-scripture-label">&#9656; The Historical Record</p>
            <p>The same story has been told for three thousand years in a hundred languages. It was never invented by a European. It was inherited from the sun cults of the ancient world.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="sw-section sw-section-alt">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-section-heading">Every Element Is a Sun Symbol</p>
          <p class="sw-section-heading" style="font-size:0.95rem;">The cinders and the hearth</p>
          <p>Vesta / Hestia, the maiden of the hearth, is the maiden of the sun. Cendrillon / Aschenputtel / Cenerentola all mean "ash-girl." To sleep in the cinders is to dwell in the place of the dead fire — the sunless night. To rise from them is to be the sun at dawn.</p>
          <p class="sw-section-heading" style="font-size:0.95rem;">The midnight transformation</p>
          <p>Midnight is the farthest point from the sun — the hinge between solar days. At the stroke of twelve the sun-maiden's glory dissolves and she returns to ashes, just as the sun descends below the horizon. The solar cycle is embedded in the clock itself.</p>
          <p class="sw-section-heading" style="font-size:0.95rem;">The pumpkin</p>
          <p>The pumpkin is a harvest symbol — the same symbol at the center of Halloween / Samhain, the festival of the dying sun. Cinderella's carriage and the jack-o'-lantern are cousins in solar mythology, both tied to the autumn when the sun weakens and the dark grows long.</p>
          <p class="sw-section-heading" style="font-size:0.95rem;">The glass slipper</p>
          <p>Glass was associated with the sun in ancient symbolism — transparent, catching and transmitting light. The slipper is the sun's token; only the true sun-maiden can wear it. The prince's search with the slipper is the sun searching the earth for its own reflection.</p>
          <p class="sw-section-heading" style="font-size:0.95rem;">The twelve strokes</p>
          <p>Twelve hours of night. Twelve signs of the zodiac. Twelve solar divisions of the ancient world. The midnight bell at twelve is the zodiac in disguise — not a random dramatic device, but the solar calendar written into the architecture of the story.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="sw-section">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-section-heading">The Fairy Godmother and the Spell</p>
          <p>She is a sorceress who casts spells and grants wishes. The word "fairy" derives from "fata" — the Latin pagan fates, the spirits of destiny worshipped across Europe for centuries before Christianity arrived to suppress them.</p>
          <div class="sw-scripture-block">
            <p class="sw-scripture-label">&#9656; Deuteronomy 18:10–12</p>
            <p>"There shall not be found among you any one that maketh his son or his daughter to pass through the fire, or that useth divination, or an observer of times, or an enchanter, or a witch, or a charmer, or a consulter with familiar spirits, or a wizard, or a necromancer. For all that do these things are an abomination unto Yahuah..."</p>
          </div>
          <p>"A Dream Is a Wish Your Heart Makes" is not merely a song. It is a creed — the gospel of astral worship set to music. It teaches that the heart's desires are sacred and that the stars are their recipients.</p>
          <div class="sw-scripture-block">
            <p class="sw-scripture-label">&#9656; Jeremiah 17:9</p>
            <p>"The heart is deceitful above all things, and desperately wicked: who can know it?"</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="sw-section sw-section-alt">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-section-heading">The Sun-Maiden Marries the Sun-King</p>
          <p>The climax of Cinderella is the solar marriage — the fertility cult's central rite. The ash-girl, revealed by the sun-token, is united with the king. The land is made right. The harvest is assured. Disney does not know it is animating a fertility rite, but the structure enforces it anyway. The myth does not need a conscious priest. It only needs a willing audience.</p>
          <div class="sw-scripture-block">
            <p class="sw-scripture-label">&#9656; The Pattern</p>
            <p>Disney did not invent the ball, the slipper, or the midnight hour. It inherited them from the sun cults. The music is new. The religion is very old.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="sw-section">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-section-heading">What Scripture Prescribes Instead</p>
          <p>The daughter of Yahuah is not a sun-maiden waiting for a prince. She does not wish upon stars. She is not rescued by a sorceress. She is redeemed by Messiah — not by a magical token but by blood, not at a ball but on a tree, not for a wedding feast she attends in borrowed finery but for a marriage supper she is prepared for by righteousness.</p>
          <div class="sw-scripture-block">
            <p class="sw-scripture-label">&#9656; Proverbs 31:30</p>
            <p>"Favour is deceitful, and beauty is vain: but a woman that feareth Yahuah, she shall be praised."</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="sw-section sw-section-alt">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-section-heading">What Cinderella Teaches a Child</p>
          <ul class="sw-list">
            <li>Your heart's desires are prayers that will be answered if you wish hard enough.</li>
            <li>Magical helpers are trustworthy and kind.</li>
            <li>Transformation through spells is the path from low estate to glory.</li>
            <li>Your value is revealed at the ball, in the gown, when the prince sees you.</li>
            <li>The right man will find you through a magical token and rescue you from your circumstances.</li>
            <li>Marriage to royalty is the highest end, and the story ends with the wedding.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>None of these are the teaching of Scripture. Not one. They are the teaching of the sun cults, rebranded for children's bedtime.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="sw-footer-quote">
        <div class="sw-summary-block">
          <p class="sw-summary-label">&#9656; Summary</p>
          <p class="sw-summary-text">Cinderella is the sun-maiden of ancient paganism — the ash-girl who rises from the hearth, marries the sun-king at the stroke of the solar hour, and teaches little girls to wish upon stars, trust in sorceresses, and measure their worth by the moment they are seen.</p>
        </div>
        <p class="sw-quote-text">"Love not the world, neither the things that are in the world. If any man love the world, the love of the Father is not in him."</p>
        <p class="sw-quote-ref">— 1 John 2:15</p>
      </section>

    </div><!-- /panel-full -->

  </div>
</BaseLayout>

<script>
  const btnQuick = document.getElementById('btn-quick');
  const btnFull = document.getElementById('btn-full');
  const btnFullCta = document.getElementById('btn-full-cta');
  const panelQuick = document.getElementById('panel-quick');
  const panelFull = document.getElementById('panel-full');

  function showQuick() {
    panelQuick.style.display = '';
    panelFull.style.display = 'none';
    btnQuick.classList.add('sw-mode-active');
    btnFull.classList.remove('sw-mode-active');
    window.scrollTo({ top: 0, behavior: 'smooth' });
  }
  function showFull() {
    panelFull.style.display = '';
    panelQuick.style.display = 'none';
    btnFull.classList.add('sw-mode-active');
    btnQuick.classList.remove('sw-mode-active');
    window.scrollTo({ top: 0, behavior: 'smooth' });
  }

  btnQuick.addEventListener('click', showQuick);
  btnFull.addEventListener('click', showFull);
  if (btnFullCta) btnFullCta.addEventListener('click', showFull);
</script>

